# ASCII typography

Use plain ASCII punctuation unless the file format or project style guide explicitly requires Unicode.

## Prefer these (ASCII)

- Apostrophe: `'` (U+0027) for contractions and string literals.
- Double quote: `"` (U+0022) for strings and quoting.
- Hyphen-minus: `-` (U+002D) for dashes, ranges in plain text, and compound words.
- Space: normal space (U+0020). Avoid no-break space (U+00A0) and narrow no-break space (U+202F) unless required.
- Ellipsis: three periods `...` (not the single character U+2026).

## Avoid these in code, paths, JSON, YAML, shell, and similar

| Avoid                               | Use instead                        |
|-------------------------------------|------------------------------------|
| U+2018/U+2019 (single curly quotes) | `'` (U+0027)                       |
| U+201C/U+201D (double curly quotes) | `"` (U+0022)                       |
| U+00AB/U+00BB (guillemets)          | `"` or `'` per language convention |
| U+2014 (em dash), U+2013 (en dash)  | `-` (U+002D) or spaces + hyphen    |
| U+2026 (ellipsis character)         | three ASCII periods `...`          |
| U+2022 (bullet)                     | `- ` at line start (Markdown list) |

## Lists

- Do **not** use the Unicode bullet (U+2022) or spaced patterns like ` • ` / `         •   ` for lists.
- Use **Markdown** list markers: hyphen + space (`- `) at the beginning of each line. Use `*` only if the file already uses that style.

## Assistant replies and comments

Apply the same rules in chat and in non-localized prose: straight quotes, ASCII apostrophe, hyphen for dashes, and `- ` for lists instead of bullet characters. This keeps copy-paste into code and terminals safe.

## Exceptions

- Follow **Unicode** punctuation when editing human-facing content that the project already localizes (e.g. French guillemets U+00AB/U+00BB in UI copy if the codebase uses them consistently).
- Do not change punctuation inside **string literals** that must match an external API or existing data.
